(1, 11, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'and from thence did the Lord scatter them abroad upon the face of all the earth.', 109, 189, 'question', 'Reflection on Scattering', 'What does it mean for us today that ''the Lord scattered them abroad upon the face of all the earth''? In what ways might God be calling us to embrace diversity and different cultures, rather than seeking uniformity? How can this scattering reflect the broader mission of God in bringing the message of redemption to all nations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'These are the generations of Shem:', 0, 34, 'connection', 'Generations Theme', 'The phrase ''These are the generations'' echoes throughout Genesis, notably in Genesis 5:1 and Genesis 10:1, where genealogies are established. This connection emphasizes the importance of lineage and God''s unfolding plan through specific families, particularly highlighting Shem''s role as a key ancestor in the lineage leading to Abraham and ultimately to Israel. Understanding these generations is crucial for grasping the narrative of redemption in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:1", "description": "Another genealogy introduction"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:1", "description": "Continuation of genealogical records"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'Shem was an hundred years old,', 35, 65, 'theology', 'Significance of Age', 'Many scholars believe the age of Shem at the time of Arphaxad''s birth (100 years) reflects God''s promise of a long lineage. This age also serves as a reminder of God''s covenant with humanity and His faithfulness across generations. The longevity of patriarchs is often seen as a sign of divine favor and blessing, which is a recurring theme in the Old Testament.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of patriarchal ages"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'and begat Arphaxad two years after the flood:', 66, 111, 'question', 'Reflection on Timing', 'Why is the timing of Arphaxad''s birth significant just two years after the flood? This detail prompts reflection on the new beginning for humanity post-flood and the establishment of God’s covenant with Noah. How does this new beginning through Shem''s line inform our understanding of God''s redemptive plan through history?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And Shem lived after he begat Arphaxad five hundred years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 88, 'connection', 'Connection to Lifespans', 'The long lifespan of Shem, living 500 years after the birth of Arphaxad, can be cross-referenced with Genesis 5:27, which notes that Methuselah lived 969 years. These extensive lifespans illustrate the early vitality of humanity and God''s initial design for life. Understanding these ages invites reflection on human mortality and divine purpose throughout biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "Methuselah''s lifespan highlights the extraordinary ages in early genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'begat sons and daughters.', 63, 88, 'theology', 'Theological Significance of Generations', 'This passage suggests the importance of family lineage in God''s plan. Many scholars believe that the generations listed in Genesis serve not only to establish historical record but also to underscore the faithfulness of God across generations. The idea of progeny reflects God''s command to ''be fruitful and multiply'' (Genesis 1:28), emphasizing the continuation of His covenant with humanity.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'Shem lived after he begat Arphaxad five hundred years,', 4, 58, 'question', 'Reflection on Lifespan', 'What does it mean for our understanding of legacy and faithfulness that Shem lived for 500 years after becoming a father? How can we apply the concept of generational faithfulness in our own families and communities today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'he begat Arphaxad', 21, 38, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight on ''begat''', 'יָלַד (yalad, H3205) - to bear, bring forth. This term emphasizes the act of parenthood as foundational in the biblical narrative, reflecting God''s creative design for human relationships and community. The use of ''begat'' signifies the importance of familial ties in the unfolding story of redemption.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for ''begat''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Arphaxad lived five and thirty years, and begat Salah:', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'This verse highlights the continuity of the genealogical line leading to significant biblical figures. The mention of Arphaxad and Salah connects with Luke 3:35-36, which traces the lineage of Jesus back to Adam, emphasizing God''s plan through generations. Understanding these connections underscores the importance of heritage in God''s redemptive history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 3:35-36", "description": "Genealogy of Jesus showing the significance of ancestral lines."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'five and thirty years', 19, 40, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Numbers', 'The age ''thirty-five'' can be seen as symbolically significant in biblical numerology. Many scholars believe that the number five often represents grace, while thirty is associated with maturity and ministry (e.g., Jesus began His ministry at thirty). Thus, this age reflects a divinely orchestrated time for fruitfulness in Arphaxad''s life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Bible Knowledge Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of numbers in biblical texts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'begat Salah', 46, 57, 'question', 'Understanding Legacy', 'What does it mean for Arphaxad to ''begat'' Salah in the context of family and legacy? How does this concept of generational inheritance influence your understanding of spiritual lineage today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'And Arphaxad lived after he begat Salah four hundred and three years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 99, 'connection', 'Generations and Legacy', 'The mention of Arphaxad living for four hundred and three years after the birth of Salah highlights the biblical theme of generational lineage. This is echoed in Genesis 5:27, where Methuselah lived 969 years, emphasizing the long lifespans of early patriarchs. Such lifespans not only illustrate God''s blessing on humanity but also the importance of family legacy in the biblical narrative.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "Methuselah''s lifespan exemplifies the significance of generational records."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'And Arphaxad lived after he begat Salah four hundred and three years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 99, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Generations', 'This passage suggests that God’s providence extends across generations, as each patriarch plays a role in the unfolding of His plan. Many scholars believe that the longevity of these figures signifies God''s ongoing work through families, establishing a lineage that ultimately leads to the fulfillment of His promises to Abraham and the nation of Israel.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'after he begat Salah', 19, 39, 'question', 'Impact of Parentage', 'What does it mean to acknowledge that Arphaxad lived after he begat Salah? How does recognizing our own spiritual or familial legacies influence our understanding of identity and purpose in God''s plan?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'four hundred and three years', 40, 68, 'greek', 'Significance of Years', 'This specific duration of life underscores the Hebrew concept of ''דּוֹר'' (dor, H1755) - generation, which emphasizes the importance of time and continuity in God''s design for humanity. The long lives of these patriarchs reflect a divine patience and an unfolding of His covenantal promises.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1755", "description": "Dor refers to a generation, highlighting the theme of lineage in Scripture."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And Salah lived thirty years, and begat Eber:', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Generational Continuity', 'This verse highlights the continuity of the genealogical line leading to significant biblical figures. Eber, whose name means ''to cross over,'' is notable in biblical history as an ancestor of Abraham (Genesis 10:21), which establishes a connection to the covenantal promises. This generational link underscores God''s faithfulness in preserving a lineage through which His redemptive plan unfolds. The references to family lineage are foundational in understanding the unfolding of God''s purposes in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:21", "description": "Eber is mentioned as an ancestor of Abraham."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And Salah lived thirty years, and begat Eber:', 0, 45, 'theology', 'Divine Providence', 'This passage suggests the doctrine of divine providence, where God orchestrates human history through familial lines. The ages and events of these patriarchs illustrate how God sovereignly guides the unfolding narrative of redemption. Many scholars believe that the meticulous recording of genealogies serves to affirm God''s ongoing involvement in history and His commitment to fulfilling His promises to humanity, especially through the lineage of Abraham and ultimately Christ.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'begat Eber:', 34, 45, 'greek', 'Hebrew Term for Begat', 'יָלַד (yalad, H3205) - to bear, bring forth. This term is significant as it emphasizes not only the act of procreation but also the continuation of God''s promise through the generations. The use of ''yalad'' in genealogies throughout the Old Testament underscores the importance of lineage in the biblical narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term meaning ''to bear.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And Salah lived thirty years, and begat Eber:', 0, 45, 'question', 'Reflection on Legacy', 'What does it mean to leave a legacy of faith as Salah did with Eber? How can we ensure that our lives contribute positively to the spiritual inheritance we pass on to future generations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'after he begat Eber', 16, 35, 'connection', 'Lineage of Promise', 'The phrase ''after he begat Eber'' connects to Genesis 12:3, where God promises that through Abraham''s lineage, all nations will be blessed. Eber is significant as the ancestor of Abraham, indicating the unfolding of God''s redemptive plan through specific lineages. This highlights the importance of genealogies in Scripture, showing God''s sovereignty in history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:3", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham about blessing nations through his descendants."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'four hundred and three years', 36, 64, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Longevity', 'The longevity of Salah, living ''four hundred and three years,'' reflects God''s providential care and the blessing of long life in the Old Testament context. Many scholars believe that these extended life spans signify God''s favor and the preservation of His chosen people during a formative period in biblical history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 11:10-26", "description": "Discussion on the significance of lifespan in genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'begat sons and daughters', 70, 94, 'question', 'Generational Impact', 'What does the mention of ''sons and daughters'' imply about the responsibilities and legacy of faith in our families? How can we actively contribute to the spiritual heritage of our descendants, much like Salah did through his lineage?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Eber lived four and thirty years', 4, 36, 'connection', 'Biblical Generational Patterns', 'The mention of Eber''s age when he begat Peleg connects to other generational patterns in Genesis, such as in Genesis 5:28-29, where Noah''s age is highlighted at the birth of his son. This pattern emphasizes the importance of lineage and the passing down of God''s promises through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:28-29", "description": "Highlights the significance of age and lineage in biblical narratives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'begat Peleg', 42, 53, 'theology', 'Significance of Naming', 'Many scholars believe that the act of naming in Scripture carries deep theological significance, as it often reflects the character or destiny of the individual. Peleg''s name, meaning ''division'' (Genesis 10:25), foreshadows the division of languages and nations at Babel, illustrating God''s sovereignty in human history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the importance of names and their theological implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And Eber lived four and thirty years', 0, 36, 'question', 'Reflection on Lifespan', 'What does Eber''s lifespan teach us about the significance of faithfulness in our time on earth? How can we apply the legacy of those who came before us, like Eber, in our own spiritual journeys?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'four and thirty years', 15, 36, 'greek', 'Understanding Time in Scripture', 'There is no direct Greek term in this Hebrew verse; however, understanding the Hebrew concept of time (H3117 - יָמִים, yamim) reflects God''s sovereignty over human history and the unfolding of His plan across generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3117", "description": "Hebrew term for ''days'', often linked to the idea of life stages and divine timing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Eber lived after he begat Peleg four hundred and thirty years', 4, 65, 'connection', 'Longevity in Genesis', 'The long lifespan of Eber, living for an additional four hundred and thirty years post-Peleg, parallels the accounts of other patriarchs in Genesis, such as Noah (Genesis 9:29) and Methuselah (Genesis 5:27). These extended lifespans illustrate God''s provision in the early human history and serve to highlight the importance of these figures in the unfolding narrative of salvation. Understanding Eber''s longevity enriches our grasp of the genealogical context leading to Abraham.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 9:29", "description": "Noah''s lifespan as a comparative figure."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "Methuselah''s long life further emphasizes early patriarchal lifespans."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and begat sons and daughters', 67, 95, 'theology', 'Family as Divine Heritage', 'This phrase, ''and begat sons and daughters,'' underscores the biblical view of family and legacy. Many scholars believe that the emphasis on progeny reflects God''s command to ''be fruitful and multiply'' (Genesis 1:28). The continuation of lineage through family ties is significant in the unfolding story of redemption, evidencing God''s faithfulness to His covenant promises across generations.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s command to multiply as foundational to understanding lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Eber lived after he begat Peleg four hundred and thirty years', 4, 65, 'question', 'Reflecting on Life Span', 'What can we learn from Eber''s four hundred and thirty years of life after the birth of Peleg? How might his extended years influence our understanding of purpose and legacy in our own lives? Consider how God’s plan unfolds through multiple generations, and reflect on what it means to live faithfully over a long duration.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And Peleg lived thirty years, and begat Reu:', 0, 44, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'Peleg''s name, which means ''division,'' is significant in understanding the context of the Tower of Babel narrative in Genesis 11. The division of languages and peoples following the tower''s construction is a pivotal moment in biblical history. This connection underscores the unfolding of God''s plan for humanity as seen in Genesis 10:25, where Peleg''s life is directly related to the division of the earth.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:25", "description": "This verse discusses the division of the earth during Peleg''s time."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And Peleg lived thirty years, and begat Reu:', 0, 44, 'theology', 'Theological Implications of Generations', 'The genealogies in Genesis serve to demonstrate God''s faithfulness through generations. Many scholars believe that the listing of names, such as Peleg and Reu, highlights God’s covenantal promises being passed down. This suggests that each generation plays a vital role in the unfolding narrative of redemption, emphasizing the importance of familial and spiritual legacies in God''s plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of genealogies in showing God''s faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'lived thirty years', 10, 28, 'question', 'Reflecting on Lifespans', 'What can we learn from the specific mention of Peleg living thirty years before becoming a father? How does this period of waiting inform our understanding of God''s timing in our own lives, especially regarding the fulfillment of promises?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'begat Reu:', 34, 44, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Begat''', 'Although this text is in Hebrew, the term ''begat'' translates the Hebrew ''yalad'' (H3205) - to bear, bring forth. This term emphasizes the continuity of life and divine purpose through generations, reflecting God''s design in creation and family.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "The Hebrew word used for ''begat,'' indicating the act of giving birth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Peleg lived after he begat Reu two hundred and nine years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 92, 'connection', 'Generational Continuity', 'The mention of Peleg living for an additional two hundred and nine years after the birth of Reu highlights the theme of generational continuity found throughout Genesis. This connects to Genesis 5:24, where Enoch''s faithful walk with God is noted, implying the importance of each generation’s legacy. The longevity of these patriarchs underscores God''s ongoing covenant with humanity and the unfolding narrative of redemption.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:24", "description": "Enoch''s walk with God emphasizes the importance of faith across generations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'two hundred and nine years', 35, 61, 'theology', 'Longevity and Divine Favor', 'Many scholars believe that the extended lifespans of the patriarchs, such as Peleg''s two hundred and nine years, reflect God''s favor and purpose in their lives. This speaks to the theological concept that God sustains life for His purposes, allowing these figures to fulfill their roles in His divine plan for humanity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Waltke, Bruce K. Genesis: A Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of patriarchal lifespans in relation to God''s covenant."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'begat sons and daughters', 67, 91, 'question', 'Reflecting on Legacy', 'What does it mean for us to ''beget'' in our own lives? Peleg''s act of begetting sons and daughters invites reflection on the spiritual and moral legacies we pass on to the next generation. How can we ensure that our lives contribute positively to the faith and values of those who follow us?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Peleg lived after he begat Reu', 4, 34, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Lived''', 'Although this text is in Hebrew, a related Greek term for ''lived'' is ζάω (zao, G2198) - to live, be alive. This term often conveys more than mere existence; it embodies the idea of living fully in accordance with God''s will. This reflects the importance of how we live our lives after significant events, such as the birth of a child.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2198", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word meaning ''to live''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'And Reu lived two and thirty years, and begat Serug:', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'The mention of Reu''s age and lineage connects to Genesis 5:32, where Noah''s sons are introduced. Both passages highlight the importance of lineage in establishing God''s covenantal promises through generations. Understanding this connection emphasizes God''s faithfulness in preserving a line through which His purposes are fulfilled.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:32", "description": "This verse discusses Noah''s sons and their significance in God''s plan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'two and thirty years', 14, 34, 'theology', 'Divine Timing', 'Many scholars believe that the ages given in genealogies signify divine order and timing in God''s redemptive plan. Each age is not just a historical fact but reflects the intentionality behind God''s unfolding narrative throughout history, illustrating how God uses time to shape His people.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'begat Serug', 40, 51, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''begat''', 'Although this passage is in Hebrew, understanding the Greek term ''γεννάω'' (gennao, G1080) - to beget or to give birth - can enrich our understanding of the concept of lineage in Scripture. It emphasizes not only physical birth but also the continuation of a legacy and God''s covenant through generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1080", "description": "This Strong''s number corresponds to the Greek term for begetting."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Reu lived two and thirty years', 4, 34, 'question', 'Reflecting on Lifespans', 'What does Reu''s age signify about the value of life and legacy in God''s plan? How can we view our own lives in the context of the generations that precede and follow us?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And Reu lived after he begat Serug two hundred and seven years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 93, 'connection', 'Longevity in Generations', 'The longevity of Reu, living 207 years after the birth of Serug, parallels the lifespans of other patriarchs, such as Noah (Genesis 9:29) and Shem (Genesis 11:11). This pattern indicates the significance of generational continuity in God''s plan, highlighting how each patriarch contributes to the unfolding story of redemption.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 9:29", "description": "Noah''s lifespan reinforces the theme of longevity in early generations."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:11", "description": "Shem''s lifespan further connects Reu''s story to the broader narrative."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'begat Serug', 23, 34, 'theology', 'Generational Blessing', 'The phrase ''begat Serug'' reflects the biblical theme of generational blessing, where the act of begetting is not merely biological but also spiritual. Many scholars believe that the lineage of Abraham, which includes Serug, is crucial for understanding God''s covenantal relationship with humanity, as it sets the stage for the eventual calling of Abraham in Genesis 12.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explores the significance of genealogies in God''s redemptive plan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'two hundred and seven years', 35, 62, 'question', 'Longevity Reflection', 'What does the extended lifespan of Reu teach us about God''s provision and purpose for each generation? How might understanding the historical context of these years shape our view of God''s faithfulness through time?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'And Serug lived thirty years, and begat Nahor:', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Lineage and Promise', 'This verse connects to Genesis 12:1-3, where God promises Abraham that through his lineage all nations will be blessed. The mention of Serug and Nahor highlights the unfolding of this covenantal promise through generations, emphasizing the importance of familial lineage in God''s redemptive plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1-3", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham, showing the significance of lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Serug lived thirty years', 4, 28, 'question', 'Significance of Age', 'What might the age of thirty symbolize in this context? In biblical tradition, the age of thirty often signifies maturity and readiness for leadership, as seen with Joseph in Genesis 41:46. How does this understanding influence our perspective on Serug''s role in the lineage leading to Abraham?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'begat Nahor', 34, 45, 'theology', 'Importance of Begat', 'The term ''begat'' emphasizes the continuity of God''s plan through generations. Many scholars believe that this genealogical record not only serves to establish historical lineage but also illustrates God''s faithfulness to His promises across time, reinforcing the theological theme of covenant.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on the significance of genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Nahor', 40, 45, 'greek', 'Nahor''s Name Meaning', 'Nahor (נָחוֹר, H5172) - snorer, to breathe. The name Nahor may reflect a spiritual state or character. In the biblical narrative, names often carry prophetic significance, hinting at the life and legacy of the individual.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5172", "description": "Strong''s number for Nahor, indicating its meaning."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And Serug lived after he begat Nahor two hundred years, and begat sons and daughters.', 0, 85, 'connection', 'Generational Continuity', 'This verse highlights the generational continuity in the lineage of Abraham, emphasizing God''s covenant through family lines. A relevant cross-reference is Genesis 12:1-3, where God promises blessings to Abraham and his descendants. This connection underscores the significance of these genealogies in establishing God''s faithfulness across generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1-3", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham and his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 11, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'two hundred years', 37, 54, 'theology', 'Longevity and Divine Purpose', 'Many scholars believe that the long lifespans recorded in Genesis serve to illustrate God''s sovereignty over life and death. The extended years of Serug reflect a divine purpose in preserving the lineage leading to Abraham, emphasizing the importance of these ancestors in the unfolding story of redemption.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on the significance of genealogies and lifespans in Genesis"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');